<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-338-462  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 338 462.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Telephony  April 9 1990 v218 n15 p53(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>A new answer to fiber protection. (an optical switch, currently intesting, offers a new level of protection from fiber disruption)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Edinger, Dennis; Duthie, Peter; Prabhakara, G.R.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>One problem with optical fiber networks is that a tremendousamount of traffic is lost when a line failure occurs.andP;  US WestAdvanced Technologies, however, is testing an optical protectionswitching technology designed by GPT Stromberg-Carlson thatreroutes traffic much faster than existing systems.andP;  The opticalswitch applications include optical multiplexing and optical crossconnection.andP;  US West is also researching the switch's fiber routeprotection potential.andP;  The switch is designed to switch traffic atrates faster than 0.15 microseconds.andP;  The speed improvement canoccur independently of existing electrical protectionarrangements.andP;  Receive switching occurs via controlling refractiveindexes that alter the incoming photons' path.andP;  The switch alsoincludes two optically isolated control interfaces and it ispolarization- independent.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   U. S. West Advanced Technologies (quality control)GPT Stromberg-Carlson (product development).andO;Topic:     Fiber opticsTestingTelecommunicationsTransmission SpeedNetworks.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   No protection. (chart)Route protection with optical switching. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>